        <h2>Multi-Platform GEO Architecture</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>A robust multi-platform GEO architecture shares a single content and entity foundation across all AI platforms, with platform-specific technical layers applied on top — avoiding the duplication of effort that comes from treating each platform as a separate project.</strong>
        </p>

        <h3>The Shared Foundation</h3>
        <p>
          The elements that benefit every AI platform simultaneously are also the highest-value GEO investments. Entity authority — consistent brand data across Wikidata, Google Knowledge Graph, LinkedIn, and industry directories — improves citation rates across all platforms that draw on knowledge graphs or training data. Content structure — declarative opening statements, FAQ sections, specific data points, clear headings — is rewarded by every retrieval system, because all of them are trying to extract clean, relevant passages from your pages. Structured data markup — Organisation, Article, FAQPage — reduces ambiguity for every AI system that processes your content.
        </p>
        <p>
          Investing in the shared foundation first delivers multi-platform benefits from a single investment. It is more efficient than making platform-specific content changes before the foundation is solid.
        </p>

        <h3>Platform-Specific Layers</h3>
        <p>
          Once the shared foundation is in place, platform-specific configuration provides the marginal gains for each channel. For Perplexity: PerplexityBot access and llms.txt implementation. For Google AI Overviews: traditional SEO signals and Google Knowledge Graph entity reinforcement. For ChatGPT: Wikipedia presence, high-authority editorial coverage, and training data presence in the publications that feed OpenAI's training corpora. For Copilot: Bing index presence and Microsoft's own entity signals.
        </p>

        <h3>Where Perplexity Fits in Execution Sequencing</h3>
        <p>
          In a phased GEO implementation, Perplexity-specific work is typically addressed in phase two or three, after the shared foundation (entity audit, schema implementation, content restructuring) is complete. The exception is PerplexityBot access — this is a phase-one technical check that takes minutes and should be completed at the very start of any GEO programme, regardless of where Perplexity sits in your strategic priority order.
        </p>
        <p>
          Phase-one shared work that benefits Perplexity along with all other platforms: entity consistency audit, FAQPage schema implementation, declarative content restructuring, and llms.txt deployment. Phase-two Perplexity-specific work: crawl frequency optimisation, content depth improvements for Pro Search, social focus mode coverage (Reddit and LinkedIn brand presence), and citation monitoring dashboards.
        </p>
        <p>
          GEOoptimised delivers <a href="/geo-services/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">multi-platform GEO programmes</a> that cover all five major AI citation channels, sequenced for maximum efficiency. The <a href="/generative-engine-optimisation/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">GEO strategy guide</a> provides the full framework context.
        </p>
